Theoretical details: molecular dynamics simulations and continuum mechanics modeling, Simulation cell: contains approximately 180,000 atoms, Axes orientation: x, y, and z axes along [112], [1̅10], and [111̅] directions respectively, Dimensions: Lx = 12.7 nm, Ly = 13.2 nm, Lz = 12.4 nm, Atomic fractions: Co, Ni, Cr, Fe, and Mn with equal atomic fractions, Potentials used: second nearest-neighbor modified embedded-atom method (2NN MEAM) potential for CoNiCrFeMn-based HEA and an EAM potential for Cu, Initial dislocation loop: radii of 4, 8, 12, 16, 20, 24, 28, 32, 36, and 40 Å introduced in the models, Shear stress application: various shear stresses applied to the dislocation loop, Energy minimization: conducted without fixing the dislocation, allowing the loop to evolve until equilibrium, Tolerance: energy and force tolerance set to 1.0e-6 eV and 1.0e-6 eV/Å respectively, Periodic boundary conditions: imposed along all three axes for homogeneous nucleation and along [111̅] and [112] directions for heterogeneous nucleation
Special conditions: No partial ordering or intermetallic phases mentioned

Name: 10.1016-j.intermet.2021.107459.txt
Experimental details: powder metallurgy involving high energy mechanical milling and thermomechanical consolidation, Elemental powders: Co, Cr, Fe, Ni, Mn (purity >99.5 wt% and particle sizes <75 μm) and FeTi master alloy (purity >99 wt% and particle sizes <75 μm), Mixing: Rotation speed of 200 rpm for 6 h, Milling: Higher rotation speed of 400 rpm for 66 h using a planetary ball mill (QM-3SP4, Nanda Instrument Plant, China), stainless steel balls, ball to powder weight ratio of 5:1, stearic acid (0.5 wt%) as PCA and source of C and O, Consolidation: Die-pressing, induction heating to 950 °C and 1000 °C with a holding time of 2 min, hot extrusion at these temperatures with an extrusion ratio of 9:1, conducted in argon atmosphere, Heat treatment: Parts of the HE1000 sample heated to 820 °C for 1 h, quenched to liquid nitrogen and water, aged at 480 °C for 16 h
Special conditions: Introduction of intragranular Ni–Ti nanoparticles through heat treatment

Experimental details: Density Functional Theory (DFT), Software: Vienna Ab initio Simulation Package (VASP), Exchange-correlation functional: Perdew-Burke-Ernzerhof (PBE) functional under the generalized gradient approximation (GGA), Pseudopotentials: Projector augmented wave (PAW), K-point grid: 6 × 6 × 6 in reciprocal space, Cutoff energy: 700 eV for the plane wave basis set, Convergence criteria: Total energies and forces were converged to 1 × 10−9 eV/atom and −1 × 10−9 eV/Å, respectively, Structural model: A randomization method was used to build the structural model for TiZrHfMoNb, considering its disordered solid solution nature. About 100 configurations of random distributions of the five metal elements were optimized, and only the lowest energy configuration was used for further hydrogenation simulation.
Special conditions: Hydrogen incorporation influences the transformation between BCC and FCC phases. The BCC phase transforms to the FCC phase when the hydrogen-to-metal ratio (H/M) reaches 1.1.

Theoretical details: Density Functional Theory (DFT), Exchange-correlation terms: Generalized Gradient Approximation (GGA) and Perdew Burke Ernzerhof (PBE) function, Pseudopotential: norm conserving, Convergence tolerances: {'energy': 1e-05, 'maximum_forces': 0.03, 'maximum_stress': 0.05, 'maximum_displacement': 0.001}, Lattice constant and density: {'NbMoTaW_RHEA': {'lattice_constant': 3.195, 'density': 14.099}}
